Developer Guidance for Accessibility of Lightning Components

lightning button icon


Description

The alternative-text attribute is indeed crucial for accessibility as it provides a textual alternative to non-text content (Button icon). Itâ€™s used by screen reader software for visually impaired users to tell them what the button does(Button Accessible name).
Example for download icon

Good code example 

           
            
                <lightning-button-icon  icon-name="utility:download" alternative-text="Download File" > </lightning-button-icon>

In this example, the alternative-text attribute is set to â€œDownload Fileâ€. This makes it clear to all users, including those using screen readers, that this button is used to download a file. Remember, the value of alternative-text should be descriptive and provide context to the functionality of the button. The screenshot highlights the screen reader behaviour and accessibility name computation for button element

Bad code example 

       
        
            <lightning-button-icon  icon-name="utility:download" > </lightning-button-icon>

In this example, the alternative-text attribute is missing. This makes it unclear to those using screen readers, that this button purpose is unknown. This screenshot displayes when alternative-text attribute is missing, the accessibility name is not computed, and the screen reader reads it as 'unlabelled'
